Playwright Tracing (in conftest.py)
What it is: Inside your setup_playwright fixture (lines 28-53), you have context.tracing.start() and context.tracing.stop(). How it works: A Playwright Trace is like a "black box" flight recorder for your tests. It doesn't just take a picture; it records network requests, console logs, and a full snapshot of the HTML so you can actually "time travel" through the failed test. The fixture uses a try / finally block.
It starts the recording before the test begins.
It yields the page to the test.
In the finally block (after the test ends), it checks if the test failed (using data saved by the Hook mentioned above). If it failed, it saves the trace as a .zip file. If it passed, it throws the recording away to save hard drive space. How to explain it to the teacher: "Standard screenshots weren't giving me enough info to debug why a test failed, so I implemented Playwright's Tracing API to record the DOM and network state, but I added logic to only save the zip file if the test actually fails."


conftest.py (lines 104-122), there is a function called pytest_runtest_makereport with a @pytest.hookimpl decorator
A Pytest Hook acts like a global "watcher". It watches the lifecycle of every test. The code basically says:
"Watch this test run."
"Did the test fail?" (if rep.when == "call" and rep.failed:)
"If yes, grab the error message, take a screenshot, and trigger the Bug Reporter." How to explain it to the teacher: "I didn't want to repeat try/except blocks for screenshots in every test, so I researched Pytest Hooks to create a centralized failure-handler that listens for failed tests automatically."


Automated Bug Reporter (utils/bug_reporter.py)
What it is: When a test fails, your code automatically generates a Jira-style .txt file and sends an email. How it works: Because of the Pytest Hook (Feature 1), the moment an assert fails, the framework grabs:
The name of the test
The """docstring""" of the test (what it was supposed to do)
The exact Python error message It formats this into a .txt file inside the bug_reports/ folder. If .env is set up, it uses Python's built-in smtplib to log into a Gmail account and email that text file to the team. "I wanted to simulate a real CI/CD (Continuous Integration) pipeline. In the real world, QA engineers need to write Jira tickets when tests fail. I used Python file I/O to auto-generate the ticket and smtplib to simulate sending an alert to developers."



The Service Layer (ShoppingService inside Services/shopping_service.py)
 In test_e2e_flows.py (line 72), instead of doing a bunch of UI clicks in the test, you use ShoppingService(tea, home).process_sale_items(total)
Page Objects (pages/): Only know how to find and click things (locators).
Service Classes (Services/): Combine multiple page actions into a business workflow (e.g., "Find all items on sale, add the cheap ones to the cart, add the expensive ones to the wishlist").
Tests (tests/): Only call the Service and then do assert checks to verify the outcome.
My end-to-end tests were getting too long and complicated. I learned about the 'Service Layer Pattern', so I moved the complex loops and business logic out of the test file and into a dedicated ShoppingService class, keeping my tests clean and focused strictly on assertions.


