Naming Rules for Pytest:
The file name must start with test_ (e.g., test_database_validation.py or test_product_data.py).
The class name must start with Test (e.g., TestProductData).
The function name must start with test_ (e.g., test_prices_against_json).


he Hashtag # (Inline Comment)
This is a standard single-line comment. Python completely ignores everything after the # on that line.

Used for: Explaining a specific line of code to another developer (or your future self).
Invisible to code tools: It is purely for humans reading the source code.



The Triple Quotes """...""" or '''...''' (Docstring)
This is called a Docstring (Documentation String). It can span multiple lines. While Python does ignore it when running the code, it does NOT throw it away. Python actually saves the docstring as an official attribute of the function or class (__doc__).

Used for: Officially documenting what a function, class, or module does.
Visible to code tools:
When you hover over a function in PyCharm, it reads the """docstring""" and shows it to you in a popup.
In your project, your BugReporter actually extracts the """docstring""" and puts it into your Jira bug report to explain what the failed test was trying to do!
pytest reporting tools (like Allure) automatically read docstrings and use them as the official "Test Description" in the visual HTML report.


Summary Rule of Thumb:
Use """...""" (Docstrings) immediately under the def line to explain the "Big Picture" of what a function or test does.
Use # (Hashtags) inside the function to explain the "How" and "Why" of specific lines of code.


